1
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:00,600
Grandma Randolph used to smile a lot.

2
00:03:01,900 --> 00:03:03,200
She said it was good for the heart.

3
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:10,800
Grandma was the first dead person I’d ever seen.

4
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:22,900
She also said there was nothing
a smile couldn’t fix.

5
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:32,700
So it started. 
An endless line of relatives

6
00:03:33,100 --> 00:03:35,200
waiting to toss dirt
on my grandmother.

7
00:03:46,900 --> 00:03:48,200
My dad loved astronomy.

8
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:51,800
Most mornings I’d wake up and find him asleep in the attic.

9
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:54,800
His telescope aimed at the horizon.

10
00:03:55,300 --> 00:03:57,300
He loved watching the moonset.

11
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:01,500
He died when I was 9.

12
00:04:25,300 --> 00:04:27,100
Relax, it's okay.

13
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:34,200
It's okay, honey. 
It's okay, Ryan

14
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:37,600
I should’ve never let him look in the casket.

15
00:04:41,100 --> 00:04:42,800
He’ll be all right.

16
00:04:43,700 --> 00:04:45,200
His cousin is of the same age and he didn’t cry.

17
00:04:45,700 --> 00:04:49,400
Tossing the dirt... 
I should have seen that coming. 

18
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:51,300
It was all too final.

19
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:55,800
He wasn’t ready for that.

20
00:04:57,400 --> 00:04:59,200
You can’t protect him from everything.

21
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:02,600
From life.

22
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:05,000
I do that?

23
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:07,800
In a way.

24
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:10,900
He keeps intact to it in his room.

25
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:14,000
He’s a boy.

26
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,600
Let him fly.

27
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:32,100
My dad told me the moon 
is a big magic ball of dust.

28
00:05:35,700 --> 00:05:36,900
And I believed him.

29
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:56,300
I used to be able to see the Man in the Moon.

30
00:05:57,500 --> 00:05:59,700
Until my mom gave me my dad’s telescope.

31
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:03,400
Then what I found up there were a bunch of craters and rocks.

32
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:06,700
It’s weird.

33
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:11,800
Sometimes, if I look at the moon without my telescope, 
I can almost see him again.

34
00:06:14,700 --> 00:06:16,500
Almost.

35
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:44,300
My dad was crazy for Gordie Hawn. 
Guy who walks on water, my dad used to say.

36
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:47,100
Frozen, of course.

37
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:16,200
Grandpa doesn’t even know Grandma is gone.

38
00:07:19,700 --> 00:07:22,100
Mom says that’s the silver lining of Alzheimer's.

39
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:28,700
Ryan, honey, why don’t you take 
your cousins outside, OK?

40
00:07:29,300 --> 00:07:32,500
Show them how to play hockey. 
Come on.

41
00:07:33,500 --> 00:07:34,500
Come on.

42
00:07:49,900 --> 00:07:52,800
Hey, did you notice one of Grandma’s eyes was open?

43
00:07:53,500 --> 00:07:55,000
You know what that means.

44
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:57,700
One of the relatives is going to die
in six months.

45
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:01,700
Maybe, one of us.

46
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,300
It’s true. 
I swear it.

47
00:08:07,500 --> 00:08:08,700
Yo, Flynnigan!

48
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:12,400
Yeah, and then he goes low and scores!

49
00:08:13,100 --> 00:08:16,800
So, you think your mom will let us go fishing in the trouter jump?

50
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:22,000
Hey!  

51
00:08:22,700 --> 00:08:24,200
Does he ever talk?

52
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:29,300
If you watch your dad get mashed by a train, you’d probably go mute, too.

53
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:32,700
Why? You’re having trouble understanding him?

54
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:38,100
All right.

55
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:43,800
I’m sorry about your Grandma. 
She was a really nice lady.

56
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:47,800
- Made us laugh. 
- It’s all right, we didn’t really know her.

57
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:52,400
- We… live in New Jersey. 
- Oh, then I’m really sorry.

58
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:56,600
Later.

59
00:08:59,300 --> 00:09:03,100
Dude, the fish are gonna be great. 
My cousin caught a 20-inch trout.

60
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:05,800
20 inches.

61
00:09:06,500 --> 00:09:09,000
Okay, it was 18.

62
00:09:17,200 --> 00:09:19,300
- Watch out, Ryan! 
- Get out of the road!

63
00:09:20,600 --> 00:09:22,100
Jackass!

64
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:27,100
You’re all right?

65
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:31,500
You’re all right?

66
00:09:31,500 --> 00:09:33,400
He didn’t really hit you, did he?

67
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,200
Are you sad, Ry? 
About your Grandma?

68
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:52,600
Hey, come on, don’t worry about it, buddy,
she’s in Heaven.

69
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:57,300
What are you, an atheist, Flynn?

70
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:01,700
Someone who doesn’t believe in God?

71
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,400
If you’re even thinking about it, 
that can’t be good.

72
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:07,600
I mean,

73
00:10:08,300 --> 00:10:10,100
if there were no God,

74
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:14,100
that would be harsh.

75
00:10:20,100 --> 00:10:22,700
Can we go for the bridge?

76
00:10:23,700 --> 00:10:28,600
No thanks, that bridge is like a pile of toothpicks. 
Besides, it’s not even a shortcut to the lake.

77
00:10:29,600 --> 00:10:32,100
But … Whatever.

78
00:11:09,300 --> 00:11:11,300
Check it out, Flynnigan!

79
00:11:12,200 --> 00:11:14,700
Am I the master or what?

80
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:18,600
Look at that, 
look at that baby.

81
00:11:19,300 --> 00:11:23,200
Oh, yeah! Oh, it’s a lively one. 
I got it, I got it.

82
00:11:24,200 --> 00:11:25,300
Hey.

83
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:27,700
Hallo?

84
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:29,900
Hallo?

85
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:34,700
I could really work in a killer well here, 
You’d only notice if it bit you in the butt.

86
00:11:39,200 --> 00:11:44,400
What’s up, dude? 
You’re like a pile of molten cheese today.

87
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:53,500
Ryan, what are you doing?

88
00:11:54,100 --> 00:11:55,000
What are you doing?

89
00:11:56,200 --> 00:11:58,000
Oh, you do it.

90
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:00,500
Come on!

91
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:17,000
- Don’t move, don’t move. 
- That hurt.

92
00:12:17,300 --> 00:12:21,900
I know, but what were you doing in the lake, when your hook was still cast? 
- Ask Flipper.

93
00:12:24,100 --> 00:12:25,500
Success!

94
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:38,400
- Yo, Ry? 
- Ryan?

95
00:12:42,700 --> 00:12:44,700
- Ryan?

96
00:12:46,500 --> 00:12:48,500
See you tomorrow.

97
00:12:49,800 --> 00:12:52,600
- Thanks, Mrs. Flynn, you saved my butt. 
- Oh, get out of here.

98
00:12:53,300 --> 00:12:54,700
Go, go, go.

99
00:13:04,200 --> 00:13:05,800
Ryan?

100
00:13:26,300 --> 00:13:28,300
Come out.

101
00:13:29,800 --> 00:13:31,200
Ryan!

102
00:13:32,600 --> 00:13:34,300
Ryan, get out of the car!  

103
00:13:37,200 --> 00:13:38,200
Oh, God!

104
00:13:43,800 --> 00:13:45,300
Dad!

105
00:14:00,300 --> 00:14:01,500
Ryan.

106
00:14:02,500 --> 00:14:04,600
Good morning Ryan, 
where do you wanna meet?

107
00:14:06,500 --> 00:14:08,200
All right, see you in five.

108
00:14:13,700 --> 00:14:16,300
Excuse me, how about asking for the phone?

109
00:14:17,100 --> 00:14:19,300
Come on, 
what is going on?

110
00:14:19,800 --> 00:14:21,600
Are you angry with me? What?

111
00:14:24,200 --> 00:14:26,600
Oh, Rocky will just have to wait. 
Besides...

112
00:14:27,100 --> 00:14:30,100
I thought we had an agreement -
on the weekends we fish together.

113
00:14:40,400 --> 00:14:46,700
All right, but next weekend it’s you and me, okay?

114
00:14:54,700 --> 00:14:56,300
All right, go on.

115
00:15:13,100 --> 00:15:14,300
Hey, slow down.

116
00:15:28,100 --> 00:15:29,200
Ryan!

117
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:37,000
You’re all right?

118
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:43,400
You’re all right?

119
00:15:57,000 --> 00:15:58,600
Ryan!

120
00:16:10,100 --> 00:16:11,500
Ryan, where are you?

121
00:16:12,400 --> 00:16:13,400
Ryan!

122
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:17,000
Ryan!

123
00:18:10,200 --> 00:18:11,800
Grandpa Randolph?

124
00:18:14,500 --> 00:18:16,600
Do you like the car? 
Outside?

125
00:18:18,300 --> 00:18:19,800
When did you start talking?

126
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:23,500
I didn’t know I stopped.

127
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:25,800
I mean, when did you start?

128
00:18:35,700 --> 00:18:39,000
- Where’s my mom? 
- Well, she’s not here.

129
00:18:51,700 --> 00:18:55,200
- Am I dead? 
- No, you’re not dead, no.

130
00:18:59,900 --> 00:19:02,800
- Where am I? 
- In your room.

131
00:19:04,200 --> 00:19:09,800
- No, things are different. 
- Well, you must have wanted them to be.

132
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:13,800
- I didn’t ask for this. 
- Frankly, neither did I, some things you don’t ask for.

133
00:19:25,100 --> 00:19:26,800
Is my dad here?

134
00:19:31,800 --> 00:19:35,400
I don’t bite, boy, just need help getting up, please.

135
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:41,300
Oh yeah, thank you, thank you very much.

136
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:54,800
- What?

137
00:19:56,600 --> 00:20:00,800
Your hand ... It just went through the glass.

138
00:20:03,600 --> 00:20:08,600
Oh yeah, that explains why you’ve been standing in the toilet there.

139
00:20:10,200 --> 00:20:12,700
You’ll have to forgive me, before
the Alzheimer's this was the bathroom.

140
00:20:14,500 --> 00:20:18,100
There was a closet. Obviously your mother renovated.

141
00:20:29,800 --> 00:20:32,400
Your father was quite a stargazer.

142
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Astronomer.

143
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:40,000
He was an astronomer.

144
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:44,600
Someday I’m gonna fly up there.

145
00:20:45,300 --> 00:20:46,800
The Moon.

146
00:20:49,100 --> 00:20:50,800
An astronaut.

147
00:20:53,700 --> 00:20:59,000
- You have a taste for adventure. 
- I never miss a shuttle launch.

148
00:21:11,400 --> 00:21:15,000
- Grandma said you were a dreamer. 
- Yeah, but sometimes ...

149
00:21:15,100 --> 00:21:21,100
You have to step back to see what’s right in front of you.

150
00:21:26,700 --> 00:21:30,600
I dream that I am good at that. 
Very good at that.

151
00:21:41,100 --> 00:21:44,700
Well, are you coming, boy, or you’re going to stay in the toilet all day?

152
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:49,800
- That’s the closet. 
- Not for me.

153
00:22:25,200 --> 00:22:27,100
- Who is that? 
- Pretty, huh?

154
00:22:28,100 --> 00:22:30,300
- Why is she wearing a coat in summer?

155
00:22:30,400 --> 00:22:32,600
Why don’t you ask her?

156
00:22:33,100 --> 00:22:35,300
Go on, turtle, chase her.

157
00:22:37,900 --> 00:22:39,500
- I’m not a turtle. 
- Prove it.

158
00:23:01,300 --> 00:23:02,900
Ryan.

159
00:23:28,700 --> 00:23:30,400
Come on out!

160
00:23:34,800 --> 00:23:39,300
- What’s the matter? You won’t get wet. 
- Of course I will.

161
00:23:39,700 --> 00:23:41,400
Of course you won’t.

162
00:23:41,900 --> 00:23:43,000
Come on.

163
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:45,900
Come on.

164
00:23:54,600 --> 00:23:56,800
That is so unfair.

165
00:23:56,800 --> 00:23:58,800
It’s always winter for me.

166
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:02,200
You’re lucky, you arrived in summer. 
Give me heat any day.

167
00:24:02,900 --> 00:24:05,200
Tahiti, now that’s the place.

168
00:24:05,300 --> 00:24:06,500
How to do that?

169
00:24:11,400 --> 00:24:12,900
- What’s your name? 
- Ryan.

170
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:17,600
- What’s yours? 
- Melanie. But I like the name Pan better.

171
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,700
Like Peter Pan, 
only a girl.

172
00:24:20,700 --> 00:24:23,300
- Oh. 
- You do believe in Peter Pan, don’t you?

173
00:24:26,100 --> 00:24:28,900
If you don’t, I couldn’t ever speak to you again. Ever.

174
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:32,100
- Why? 
- It would mean you have no imagination.

175
00:24:33,300 --> 00:24:34,300
So?

176
00:24:35,200 --> 00:24:37,300
- Do you believe? 
- Sure.

177
00:24:39,300 --> 00:24:41,700
- Have you been to the factory? 
- What factory?

178
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:43,900
Oh, excellent, I get to take you!

179
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:47,900
Come on.

180
00:25:05,100 --> 00:25:06,400
What’s the matter?

181
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:14,900
Ryan?

182
00:25:17,500 --> 00:25:19,000
It’s nothing.

183
00:25:21,100 --> 00:25:22,600
Let’s go.

184
00:25:26,800 --> 00:25:28,000
Come on.

185
00:25:28,600 --> 00:25:30,600
Let’s go, slowmo.

186
00:25:42,400 --> 00:25:45,300
Pretty creepy, huh? 
He runs the show.

187
00:25:49,600 --> 00:25:51,100
How long have you been here?

188
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:57,100
A while, I guess. Time is kind of unimportant here in the Dust Factory.

189
00:25:57,700 --> 00:26:00,900
That’s how you call this place? 
The Dust Factory?

190
00:26:01,600 --> 00:26:05,200
Yup, a kind of home away from home until you’re ready to go back.

191
00:26:06,500 --> 00:26:07,700
Which I’m not!

192
00:26:08,200 --> 00:26:10,200
You’ve got to see how the big top works to understand.

193
00:26:11,700 --> 00:26:12,500
Come on.

194
00:27:03,100 --> 00:27:05,300
Who are all these people?

195
00:27:05,300 --> 00:27:08,500
People like you and me. 
We’re stuck here.

196
00:27:09,600 --> 00:27:11,200
Stuck?

197
00:28:28,800 --> 00:28:30,600
It’s called getting dusted.

198
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:37,300
You see, when you decide to make the leap, you only get one chance to fly.

199
00:28:38,600 --> 00:28:43,700
So, either you make it and move on, or get dusted and go back home.

200
00:28:45,700 --> 00:28:49,400
That’s the only way to go home? To jump and miss?

201
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:52,200
No one’s getting me up there.

202
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:20,400
- Wow, so she made it. 
- Yep, she moved on.

203
00:29:21,400 --> 00:29:23,200
Complex, isn’t it?

204
00:29:26,600 --> 00:29:31,000
- Hey, do you like to spin? 
- I don’t know what you mean.

205
00:29:32,100 --> 00:29:35,300
Spin, in circles till you get queasy and see double. Spin!

206
00:29:49,900 --> 00:29:53,700
- Bet I could ride this longer than you? 
- Yeah, right. I can go forever without puking.

207
00:29:54,200 --> 00:29:55,700
Bet you can’t!

208
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:02,000
I’m gonna win!

209
00:30:06,700 --> 00:30:07,800
Come on.

210
00:30:12,400 --> 00:30:13,700
Oh, careful.

211
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:21,500
Don’t feel bad about puking. 
I always win.

212
00:30:22,500 --> 00:30:25,500
I wasn’t puking. 
I was spitting.

213
00:30:31,300 --> 00:30:35,600
- See you tomorrow? 
- Not tomorrow. Just see you.

214
00:30:45,200 --> 00:30:51,100
- She’s a nice girl? 
- I guess. Have you been to the factory?

215
00:30:51,900 --> 00:30:56,300
Sure. Joined the crowd once, but didn’t jump, of course.

216
00:30:56,500 --> 00:30:59,300
Yeah, I’m definitely not big on jumping.

217
00:30:59,700 --> 00:31:02,300
- And I don’t like that dust. 
- Can’t blame you.

218
00:31:14,800 --> 00:31:16,200
Falling all that way...

219
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:22,900
- How do you know if you’re ready? 
- I'm certainly no expert.

220
00:31:23,400 --> 00:31:25,100
I suppose it’s different for everyone.

221
00:31:27,100 --> 00:31:31,100
Some folks probably dawdle around here quite a while, trying to figure that out.

222
00:31:31,500 --> 00:31:33,700
Melanie, for instance...

223
00:31:34,600 --> 00:31:37,400
- She... She seems a bit of a dawdler. 
- I don’t mind dawdling,

224
00:31:37,500 --> 00:31:38,700
if it means not having to jump.

225
00:31:38,900 --> 00:31:40,500
Hitting that floor looked awful painful.

226
00:31:41,300 --> 00:31:45,400
You’re afraid of a little pain. 
That’s an overrated phobia.

227
00:31:46,400 --> 00:31:48,000
- So, what’s it like? 
- What?

228
00:31:48,700 --> 00:31:49,900
You know, dying.

229
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:54,700
I don't know.

230
00:31:55,500 --> 00:31:57,900
Well, you must.
You’re practically dead.

231
00:31:58,700 --> 00:32:01,900
Thank you. 
Thank you very much.

232
00:32:02,800 --> 00:32:06,300
- It’s gotta hurt. 
- Hurt? Life hurts, boy.

233
00:32:07,200 --> 00:32:10,500
Boxing. That’s a real pain. 
I was a boxer myself.

234
00:32:10,900 --> 00:32:12,700
Not a good one,
but I was a boxer.

235
00:32:13,700 --> 00:32:14,900
Come on.

236
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:18,800
Now box, box, box!

237
00:32:24,900 --> 00:32:25,600
More, more.

238
00:32:31,200 --> 00:32:33,400
You're too strong for me.

239
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:47,800
- I heard you called me a dawdler. 
- Not me.

240
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:51,300
- I didn’t. 
- Promise you didn’t?

241
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:54,000
- If it means you’re letting go, I promise. 
- Mean it?

242
00:32:54,200 --> 00:32:57,300
Yes, I mean it. 
Let go.

243
00:32:57,300 --> 00:32:58,800
Better mean it.

244
00:33:04,800 --> 00:33:07,600
- Doesn’t this day ever end? 
- What do you mean?

245
00:33:08,900 --> 00:33:10,800
Well, there is a beginning, but no end.

246
00:33:11,800 --> 00:33:13,000
How do you know it began?

247
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:15,000
Well, it had to.

248
00:33:15,700 --> 00:33:21,900
- Or it wouldn’t be. 
- That’s not true. It just is what it is.

249
00:33:22,300 --> 00:33:24,000
You know, light all the time.

250
00:33:25,400 --> 00:33:27,700
Maybe, if we run away from the sun, 
we’ll find night.

251
00:33:29,400 --> 00:33:32,900
Let’s go east. 
